  "texts": [
    "This way, for any state s, the agent only needs to find one action that maximizes the value of q * because it effectively stores the results for all searches one step ahead.",
    "It gives the optimal expected return as a local and immediately available value for each state-action pair.",
    "It allows one to select optimal actions without knowing the possible successor states with their respective values or, in other words, the dynamics of the environment.",
    "Bellman's equations allow for finding optimal policies.",
    "Still, they are rarely used in practice, as they demand exhaustive searches in the space of states and actions besides assuming that the dynamics of the environment are precisely known, which is not always true."
